	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />A <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Netlist" class="postlink">netlist</a> is a low-level description of all the gates in a circuit and how they are connected, written in a simple HDL that resembles Boolean algebra. One might construct this by decapping a mapper, taking a photomicrograph, and identifying gates. (Lately, Quietust has been <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php?limit=50&amp;tagfilter=&amp;title=Special%3AContributions&amp;contribs=user&amp;target=Quietust&amp;namespace=&amp;year=2011&amp;month=1" class="postlink">reading the PPU and APU photos</a> to discover not-yet-documented behaviors, but at a higher level than netlists.) The resulting netlist can be synthesized into a CPLD, FPGA, or ASIC, allowing accurate clones of more complex mappers like MMC3, RAMBO-1, FME-7, later VRCs, and MMC5.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


